The cost of reaching the Moon is probably much lower now than it was in the 1960s, but not by that kind of magnitude. In any case much of this reduction results from government-sponsored research in one way or another.  <br>
<br>
Without the basic groundwork being done, there is just no incentive for private enterprise to undertake this kind of development. <br>
<br>
There is such a thing as government laying the groundwork, creating the conditions, for private enterprise as a kind of collective investment. After all, private enterprise has profited enormously from the Interstate Highway System, and knew beforehand that it would. It was still quite impossible to build the system with private capital.<br>
<br>
In any case, as better technologies are developed, they can be incorporated into the program. The existence of a goal and a program creates the incentive to develop these capabilities. <br>
<br>
As far as health-care and education are concerned, you know as well as I do that NASA's entire budget would be a drop in the bucket compared to the amounts devoted to these purposes now. <br>
Besides, what if the cure for cancer ends up being scraped off the bottom of a Martian rock? or (much more realistically) a breakthrough in gerontology results from research in the low gravity conditions of the Moon?  <br>
<br>
I do not regard this as dream fulfillment. I regard this as the human future, the next natural stage of human expansion. Practical space colonies may be 100 years away, or more, but they are the ultimate objective. By &quot;practical&quot; I mean profitable, and livable. <br>
As with the Interstate system, though, we can't get there from here with the annual profit-loss statements of individual firms controlling the objectives. <br>
<br>
I can make predictions, too: If someone else, China or India or others, begins to exploit the riches of space before we do because we wouldn't spend the money to lay the groundwork, the Americans of that future will curse this present generation for its short-sightedness and dogmatism.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=stilgar@nuclearspace>Stilgar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 96<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/10/04 1:25 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=993.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   not illogical.</span><hr size=1> It's not cheaper because _time elapses_  it's cheaper because technology advances.  You're misunderstanding my argument if you think I'm being illogical.<br>
<br>
Back in the 70's only the government was involved in space technology.  Any advancements we needed to go to the moon had to come out of taxpayer pockets.  As a result of the government way of doing things (cost plus contracts etc.) the whole project was ridiculously expensive.<br>
<br>
As I mentioned, we've got a burgeoning space economy with new aerospace companies popping up from all over the place.  Xcor Aerospace, Armadillo Aerospace, Orbital Sciences, Scaled Composites...  they're all realtively new companies working with space technology and funding it (at least mostly) from internal sources.<br>
<br>
Let them make money and, necessarily, they'll develop better techology.  It's just capitalisim.  It's what we Americans do best.<br>
<br>
The reason it's more expensive to go to the moon (I'll bet it is, anyway... its probably not significantly cheaper) now than it was in the 70's is that the government paid for it and dominated the technology as proprietary and secret so that the evil commies couldn't get ahead.  Essentially minimal progress has been made since then.  The first new operational American rocket engine since the shuttle flew in 2002.  That's basically 20 years of NO new engine development.  Can you imagine 20 years of no new CPU development in the computer industry?  <br>
I'm getting off topic.  Sorry.<br>
<br>
In another 15 years(maybe sooner, if Xcor does well), you'll be able to buy a ticket to visit low earth orbit for a few thousand (20,000? 50,000?) dollars.  The government contractors hired to build the space station and moon base and whatever else they decide to toss in as 'necessary' to inflate the cost and line their pockets would look silly claiming it still costs thousands of dollars/lb at that point, and will necessarily lower their prices.<br>
The added competition from the little guys that have proven themselves competent by being sucessful businesses will further drop the price of government contracts.<br>
<br>
Ultimately, it can be summarized like this:<br>
<br>
The growing privatization of the space economy will lead to greater efficiencies in launch and payload delivery technology, with subsequent reductions in cost and price.<br>
<br>
